occurrenceRemarks: Approximately 4 feet tall, this specimen has long green needles, some with tan tips, averaging 6 inches long. Tan-brown cones are present at the top of the stem, which is brown in color. In the vicinity of this specimen are those of the same species that are about 100 feet tall, so this is likely a juvenile. The cones are characteristic of gymnosperms, particularly conifers. The needle-like leaves indicate that this is a pine tree. The consistent geographical distribution, the height, the long needles, and the fact that the specimen is a tree all support that this is a longleaf pine. Weather conditions: overcast, 56°, windy Source: http://www.southeasternflora.com/view_flora.php?plantid=380# http://florida.plantatlas.usf.edu/Plant.aspx?id=3905

verbatimLocality: Lettuce Lake Park, Tampa, FL, US
occurrenceRemarks: Found at Lettuce Lake Park. Approximately 45°F was the temperature outside. Sunny with a cold breeze. The pine cone was spotted on the floor next to its tree. The pinecones were rounder and bigger on the upper half of it compared to the bottom half. The pincenone was spiky. The leaves of the tree were thin and tall and this is a clear identification of the species this tree belongs to which is that of a longleaf pine (shown in identification title). This was identified with the help of: https://plants.ces.ncsu.edu/plants/all/pinus-palustris/. In addition, the following organism's ecological dispersion is the surrounding areas of Florida in the USA which include Virginia, North Carolina, South Carolina, Georgia, Alabama, Mississippi, Louisiana and E Texas (https://www.conifers.org/pi/Pinus_palustris.php). It's ecology isn't limited to the USA as this organism can also be found in other habitats which include sandy uplands (uphills) and flatwoods. Finally, this organism is a seeded vascular plant, specifically a gymnosperm as they have seeds and no fruits to protect them.
name: Pinus palustris Mill.

verbatimLocality: Lettuce Lake Park, Tampa, FL, US
occurrenceRemarks: This organism was found growing on the side of a trail in Lettuce Lake Park. The organism appears to be a tree with scaly brown bark covering the truck and branches of the organism. The leaves on this plant are needle-like with a green or brown color. The needle-like leaves appear to have a waxy cuticle. There where a few pine cones found at the base of the organism. These cones are the female megaspore of the tree. Based on these characteristics and reproductive structures of the organism, it can be identificed as a Pinus palustris. The observation of this organism was made on January 20, 2019 in the afternoon. The weather was slightly cloudy and around 54 degrees Fahrenheit. The species is known to grow in the southeastern region of the United States. The organism belongs to the Kingdom Plantae, Phylum Pinophyta, Class Pinopsida, Order Pinales, Family Pinaceae, Genus Pinus, and Species palustris. https://www.conifers.org/pi/Pinus_palustris.php
name: Pinus palustris Mill.

occurrenceRemarks: The Longleaf Pine can be classified under Kingdom Plantae, and more specifically as a gymnosperm due to the tree producing cones. This individual tree was approximately 70 feet in height. Its leaves were in the shape of pine needles, and it produced cones which contained its reproductive material. The cone was 7 inches tall and pine leaves were mostly inhabiting the upper 20 feet of the tree. According to https://www.longleafalliance.org/what-is-longleaf/the-ecosystem/habitats , Longleaf Pines inhabit south-eastern United states ranging from the Carolinas to Florida, then around Gulf of Mexico's bordering states including Texas. This pine can inhabit different habitats, but this specific Pine was located in a "flatwoods" area. In addition, the website explains that the needles from in bunches of 3 and the cones average at 11 inches. This specific tree was located in Stark Park, Fl and was neighboring several other Longleaf Pines. Due to its height, the tree was receiving plenty of sunlight and nourishment.
name: Pinus palustris Mill.

occurrenceRemarks: This type of tree is categorized as a gymnosperm and is a Longleaf pine tree. The size of this tree is very tall and looks very strong wooded. The color of the organism is a brown rough trunk with spiky needle like eaves. This organism is a gymnosperm because of its vascularity and naked seed such as the pine cone which fell has fallen on the ground. This longleaf pine is considered as a type of conifer which has a very scaly bark. One characteristic that defines this organism to its taxonomic group are the above mentioned needle leaves and sheer size of the tree itself. This tree was found in lettuce lake park on a sunny day around 1:09 PM with a temperature of 78 degrees Fahrenheit. The habitat in which this tree was found in was a dry area of flat land surrounded by many other longleaf pines and small fungi sprouting from the barks. The general geographic distribution of these pines are usually in warm, wet and temperate climes such as Florida, Virginia and west to Texas. The full classification of this longleaf pine is kingdom platae, phylum coniferophyta, order pinales, family pinaceae, genus pinus, and species pinus palustris. http://web.fscj.edu/David.Byres/longleaf/palustris.htm https://www.fs.fed.us/database/feis/plants/tree/pinpal/all.html

occurrenceRemarks: Domain: Gymnosperm Kingdom: Plantae Division: Pinophyta Class: Pinopsida Order: Pinales Family: Pinaceae Genus: Pinus Description: The bark is thick, reddish-brown, and scaly. The leaves are dark green and needle-like, and occur in bundles of three. They often are twisted and 2045 cm (7.917.7 in) in length. The cones, both female seed cones (ovulate strobili) and male pollen cones (staminate strobili), are initiated during the growing season before buds emerge. Pollen cones begin forming in their buds in July. Pollination occurs early the following spring, with the male cones 38 cm (1.23.1 in) long. The female (seed) cones mature in about 20 months from pollination; when mature, they are yellow-brown in color, 1525 cm (5.99.8 in) long, and 57 cm (2.02.8 in) broad, opening to 12 cm (4.7 in), and have a small, but sharp, downward-pointing spine on the middle of each scale. The seeds are 79 mm (0.280.35 in) long, with a 2540 mm (0.981.57 in) wing. Distribution: Natural range includes most of the Atlantic and Gulf Coastal Plains from southeastern Virginia to eastern Texas and south through the northern two-thirds of peninsular Florida. The species also grows in the Piedmont, Ridge and Valley, and Mountain Provinces of Alabama and northwest Georgia. Habitat: warm, wet temperate climates characterized by hot summers and mild winters. -Longleaf pine forests are rich in biodiversity. They are well-documented for their high levels of plant diversity, in groups including sedges, grasses, carnivorous plants, and orchids.
name: Pinus palustris Mill.

occurrenceRemarks: This ID was made in a forest area with in Lettuce Park, which makes the organism a wild one. The park is a conservation park. The temperature around 88-89 degrees Fahrenheit with sunny skies and high humidity. There was no precipitation and low winds around 3.4 mph. The environment didn't have a lot of mosquitos, but have a few of love bugs. The tree thrived amongst many other species of plants and forest land. The tree was very tall with vines traveling up its dark brown peeling bark trunk. The tree also features long needles coming off its branches. Due to the distinctive color/pattern of the tree trunk and shape of it's leaves, I was able to identify the organism. The inaturalist suggestions included "Longleaf Pine" on its list and the park had the tree labeled as that as well. I also went on the Arbor Day Foundation tree guide website (https://www.arborday.org/trees/treeguide/treedetail.cfm?itemID=1095) and compared the actual tree as well as surrounding structures to the pictures I took. I found heavy similarities, so believe this is the correct ID.
name: Pinus palustris Mill.

occurrenceRemarks: Pinus palustris (Gymnosperm) This gymnosperm was observed at Lettuce Lake Park on October 7, 2018 at 2:59 PM. It was a cloudy day; approximately 86 degrees. This evergreen conifer stood very tall in a dry environment; it had needlelike leaves and the bark was thick and scaly. The leaves were very long (12-18 inches in length). There were exactly 3 needles per fascicle. The pine cones were large; approximately 6-10 inches long, narrowly ovoid or cylindrical. Careful speculation of these characteristics lead this tree to be identified as the Long-leaf Pine (Pinus palustris). Identified using: https://www.nwf.org/Educational-Resources/Wildlife-Guide/Plants-and-Fungi/Longleaf-Pine

occurrenceRemarks: This observation was made at 5:26pm with an i phone x camera. Weather: hot and sunny with the temperature being 88 degrees Fahrenheit with 56% humidity levels. Habitat: This tree was found in a densely packed forest surrounded by other large trees and diverse vegetation. This observation was concluded to be a Longleaf Pine. This pine tree is considered an evergreen conifer. It has the longest needle like leaves of all the pines growing up to 18in long with the leaves showing in bundles of threes. They can grow up to 80-100ft tall. They are covered in thick brown scaly bark that grow perfectly up. The lower branches of the trees are naturally pruned. They can be found in many different climate types and require sunlight to grow. These characteristics of the plant and the habitat are consistent with my observation. These conifers are distributed across southeastern Virginia to Florida, westward to Louisiana and to eastern Texas. Source: https://www.nwf.org/Educational-Resources/Wildlife-Guide/Plants-and-Fungi/Longleaf-Pine Gymnosperm
name: Pinus palustris Mill.

occurrenceRemarks: The needlelike leaves, which come in bundles of three, can grow up to 18 inches (46 centimeters) long. Mature trees stand 80 to 100 feet (24 to 30 meters) tall. The single trunk, which is covered in thick, scaly bark, reaches up to three feet (0.9 meters) in diameter. The trees naturally prune their lower branches and grow almost perfectly straight. - NWF.org This longleaf pine was approximately 3 feet tall. Longleaf pine now are only found in 3 percent of their original range of 90 million acres. Conservation of the tree is important to the biodiversity of over 30 endangered and threatened species. For example the red-cockaded woodpeckers rely on longleaf pines for their habitat. RCWs are unique in their nesting, as they only nest in self-made cavities in live pine trees, as opposed to dead trees which most woodpeckers prefer. Resin wells are also excavated by RCWs below their cavities to prevent predators from climbing cavity trees and robbing nests. 2006, FWC began a statewide RCW Safe Harbor Program through an agreement with the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service under the Federal Endangered Species Act (ESA). The goal of the program is to help conserve the RCW through partnerships with private landowners. Since RCWs are protected under the ESA, landowners have a legal obligation to protect the birds and their habitat. The program currently includes 15 private properties and approximately 65,000 acres. Safe Harbor Agreements make sense whenever landowners are interested in restoring or enhancing habitats that may benefit this endangered species but are concerned about incurring additional regulatory restrictions on the use of their land. It effectively freezes a landowner's ESA responsibilities as long as the owner agrees to restore, enhance, or create habitat that benefits red-cockaded woodpeckers. The Safe Harbor Program has many benefits to landowners, but the primary incentive is the certainty they gain regarding future land use. Property owners can maintain, restore or enhance red-cockaded woodpecker habitat, with the assurance that additional birds will not result in more land use restrictions. The program is voluntary and a landowner can withdraw from it at any time - MyFWC.com
